Definition

A token is the smallest unit of text that a Large Language Model (LLM) processes. A token can be a whole word, part of a word, punctuation, or even a single character depending on the tokenizer.

Real-world Analogy

Think of building a LEGO model. Instead of seeing the whole castle, you first separate it into individual LEGO blocks. Similarly, an LLM breaks text into tokens before processing it.

Salesforce Example

If a user asks:

"Generate an Apex class to update Account records."

The AI first breaks this sentence into tokens before understanding and generating the code.

